What you have in the owner field of a classroom document looks like an email address, not a Firebase Authentication UID.  That&#39;s not ever going to compare to `request.auth.uid`.  It looks like the document does have a UID in the uid field.  You should probably be using that for your security rules, not an email address.

    allow update, delete, create: if classroomData().uid == request.auth.uid;

But since you&#39;re comparing the UID to the current document being matched by security rules, you don&#39;t need to get() that document.  You can access the properties of the current document being written using `resource`:

    allow update, delete, create: if resource.data.uid == request.auth.uid;

You can simplify even further.  Since `write` access is the same as the combination of `update`, `delete`, and `create`, you can write the rule like this:

    allow write: if resource.data.uid == request.auth.uid;

